WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:07.360
<v Teacher><i>To do</i>, or <i>to make</i> in Spanish is <b>hacer</b>. And it has a silent <i>h</i>.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.480
<v Teacher>It's <i>h-a-c-e-r</i>.

00:00:10.519 --> 00:00:18.439
<v Teacher>So in most of Spain actually that would sound <b>ha/th/er</b>. But <b>ha/s/er</b> in most of the Spanish speaking world.

00:00:18.619 --> 00:00:19.980
<v Teacher>What verb type is it?

00:00:19.980 --> 00:00:21.099
<v Teacher>What is the ending?

00:00:21.099 --> 00:00:21.660
<v Student><i>-er</i>.

00:00:22.460 --> 00:00:28.699
<v Teacher>So actually whenever we come across a new verb, we want to make a mental note what is the ending.

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:31.279
<v Teacher>Or, rather than make a mental note, just process it.

00:00:31.279 --> 00:00:34.079
<v Teacher>Remember we always want to do anything but memorize,

00:00:34.079 --> 00:00:39.040
<v Teacher>so just looking and going "<b>hacer</b>, <i>-er</i> verb, ok". Just to get in that habit.

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:41.340
<v Teacher>If we know it's an <i>-er</i> verb, we know how to work with it.

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:49.100
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>he's doing</i> or <i>making</i>, <i>she is doing</i> or <i>making</i>, <i>you are</i> (formal) <i>doing</i> or <i>making</i>?

00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:51.380
<v Student><b>Hace.</b>

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:52.180
<v Teacher><b>Hace.</b>

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:52.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:55.940
<v Teacher><i>You're doing it:</i>

00:00:55.940 --> 00:00:57.060
<v Student><b>Lo hace.</b>

00:00:57.060 --> 00:00:57.940
<v Teacher><b>Lo hace.</b>

00:00:57.940 --> 00:01:01.780
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>they're doing it</i> or <i>you guys are doing it</i>?

00:01:02.559 --> 00:01:04.320
<v Student>Los hacen.

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:05.519
<v Student>Lo hacen.

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:06.560
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:07.759
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:01:07.759 --> 00:01:09.920
<v Teacher><b>Lo hacen.</b>

00:01:10.159 --> 00:01:13.200
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal) <i>are doing it.</i> So what is the sound for informal you?

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:18.260
<v Student><b>Hacen.</b>

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:22.420
<v Teacher>So for informal <i>you</i> we add on an <i>s</i> to the <i>he/she/it</i> version.

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:24.180
<v Teacher>So we get:

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:24.980
<v Student><b>Haces.</b>

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:26.100
<v Teacher><i>You're doing it:</i>

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:28.080
<v Student><b>Lo haces.</b>

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:28.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.560
<v Teacher>The word for <i>what</i> in Spanish is <b>qué</b>.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:35.360
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>what are you doing?</i>

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:37.000
<v Student><b>¿Qué haces?</b>

00:01:37.759 --> 00:01:39.600
<v Teacher><b>¿Qué haces?</b> And this is a way of saying <i>how are you</i> as well.

00:01:40.479 --> 00:01:41.200
<v Teacher><i>what are you doing?</i>,

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:42.479
<v Teacher><i>what are you up to?</i>

00:01:42.719 --> 00:01:43.200
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:55.759
<v Teacher>So we see that for <i>-ar</i> verbs, we have the principle sound of /a/, and then we add our <i>n</i> or <i>s</i>, <i>n</i> for <i>they</i> or <i>you</i> (plural), and <i>s</i> for informal <i>you</i>.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:02:04.680
<v Teacher>And for <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs we have the key sound /e/, and we're adding on <i>s</i> for informal <i>you</i>, <i>n</i> for <i>they</i>, <i>you</i> (plural).

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:06.280
<v Teacher>Now these associations

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:15.100
<v Teacher>between <i>s</i> and informal <i>you</i>, and <i>n</i> and <i>they</i> or <i>you guys</i>, we're going to see all throughout the Spanish verb structure.

00:02:15.060 --> 00:02:17.060
<v Student>So this confuses me a little bit;

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:19.220
<v Student>isn't this also a memorization?

00:02:19.220 --> 00:02:23.140
<v Student>Having to remember which ending goes with what people?

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:27.820
<v Teacher>There's a difference between memorization and remembering, ah?

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:31.740
<v Teacher>We can remember through not actively trying to memorize.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:35.700
<v Teacher>So not telling you you shouldn't remember anything, you need to remember Spanish.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:45.860
<v Teacher>I'm telling you that you're going to remember it much easier without the active process of trying to memorize anything, which blocks whichever processes we need for remembering.

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:50.060
<v Teacher>I like to describe it in this way: that you borrow information when you memorize it,

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:56.700
<v Teacher>but when you are applying it practically in this construction of these sentences, when you're looking from many different angles

00:02:56.440 --> 00:03:00.200
<v Teacher>at the elements that we are looking at in Spanish, then you are internalizing it.

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:02.840
<v Teacher>Then it's really yours, you're not borrowing it.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:09.080
<v Teacher><b>Puedo</b> in Spanish means <i>I can</i>, <i>I am able</i>.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:10.540
<v Teacher><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:11.340
<v Student><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:11.820
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:11.820 --> 00:03:14.060
<v Teacher><i>P-u-e-d-o</i>.

00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:15.020
<v Teacher><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:15.020 --> 00:03:15.820
<v Student><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:21.660
<v Teacher>You're probably noticing as well that the <i>d</i> is quite soft when it comes in the middle of a word in Spanish, rather than a hard /d/.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:23.700
<v Teacher><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:24.740
<v Student><b>Puedo.</b>

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:31.060
<v Teacher>So <b>puedo</b> means <i>I can</i>, or <i>I am able</i>, and the "to" form of the verb is an <i>-er</i> verb.

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:33.140
<v Teacher>So <b>puedo</b> is an <i>-er</i> verb.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:39.540
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>he can</i> or <i>she can</i> or <i>it can</i> or <i>you</i> (formal) <i>can</i>?

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:40.340
<v Student><b>Puede.</b>

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:41.060
<v Teacher>And how would you say informally <i>you can</i>?

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:44.500
<v Student><b>Puedes.</b>

00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:46.700
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:51.900
<v Teacher>Now in English, we don't say <i>can you to come?</i>, but it's what we mean.

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:53.420
<v Teacher>Now this is an English problem;

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:55.340
<v Teacher>the English is taking the <i>to</i> away here;

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:56.540
<v Teacher>it does it sometimes.

00:03:56.540 --> 00:03:58.140
<v Teacher>You don't say <i>I must to come</i>,

00:03:58.140 --> 00:03:59.260
<v Teacher>you say <i>I must come</i>,

00:03:59.459 --> 00:03:59.860
<v Teacher>no?

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:02.019
<v Teacher><i>I am able to come</i>.

00:04:02.019 --> 00:04:06.819
<v Teacher>You can think of it this way as we thought of <i>I must come</i> as <i>I owe to come</i>.

00:04:06.819 --> 00:04:11.459
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>can you come?</i> Talking informally?

00:04:12.420 --> 00:04:15.700
<v Student><b>Puede</b> - sorry, informal. <b>¿Puedes venir?</b>

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:17.140
<v Teacher><b>¿Puedes venir?</b>

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:19.940
<v Teacher>So this is what we're going to be using to talk with friends,

00:04:19.940 --> 00:04:22.180
<v Teacher>no, this <i>s</i>. We're going to be hearing it a lot.

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:26.020
<v Teacher>If it helps you make the association, you might have heard <b>¿cómo estás?</b>,

00:04:25.639 --> 00:04:26.440
<v Teacher><i>how are you?</i>

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:30.600
<v Teacher>The <i>s</i> on the end of <b>estás</b> there is this informal <i>s</i>.

00:04:30.759 --> 00:04:32.120
<v Teacher><b>Puedes</b>.

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:34.199
<v Teacher>So, <i>can't you come?</i>:

00:04:34.199 --> 00:04:36.000
<v Student><b>¿No puedes venir?</b>

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.699
<v Teacher><b>¿No puedes venir?</b> <i>Why can't you come?</i>:

00:04:38.699 --> 00:04:41.000
<v Student><b>¿Por qué no puedes venir?</b>

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
<v Teacher><b>¿Por qué no puedes venir?</b> <i>I want to know why you can't come</i>:

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:45.180
<v Student><b>Quiero</b> -

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:47.260
<v Student>oh to know.

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:51.740
<v Student>Ok I'm going <i>know</i> and <i>knowledge</i> and that's not taking me anywhere.

00:04:51.740 --> 00:04:53.340
<v Teacher>Boy's got <i>savvy</i>…

00:04:53.340 --> 00:04:54.220
<v Student>Ah, yes.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:56.380
<v Teacher>So <i>I want to know</i>:

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.080
<v Student><b>Quiero saber.</b>

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:02.560
<v Teacher><b>Quiero saber.</b> <i>Why</i>:

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:03.520
<v Student><b>Por qué.</b>

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:05.680
<v Teacher><i>You can't come</i>:

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:07.740
<v Student><b>No puedes venir.</b>

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:08.460
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:05:08.460 --> 00:05:09.260
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:16.060
<v Teacher>If you address each part, part by part, and apply all of our mental energy just to the part we need and then forget it.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:18.780
<v Teacher><b>Quiero saber por qué no puedes venir.</b>

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:20.780
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:26.540
<v Teacher>So to recap, we have <i>-ar</i> verbs and we have <i>-er/-ir</i> verbs.

00:05:26.420 --> 00:05:33.220
<v Teacher>For all of the verbs, we take off the ending, <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, <i>-ir</i>, and we put <i>-o</i> for the "I" version.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.980
<v Teacher>So <b>vender</b> is <i>to sell</i> and <i>I sell</i> is:

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:39.220
<v Student><b>Vendo.</b>

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:40.100
<v Teacher><b>Vendo.</b> <b>Comprar</b> is <i>to buy</i> and <i>I buy</i> is:

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:41.000
<v Student><b>Compro.</b>

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
<v Teacher><b>Compro.</b> Good. <b>Llegar</b> is <i>to arrive</i>. <b>Llegar</b>. And <i>I arrive</i> is:

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:54.940
<v Student><b>Llegaro</b>...

00:05:54.940 --> 00:05:56.300
<v Student>oh <b>llego</b>.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:57.419
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:01.340
<v Teacher>So with this rule we can take any verb and we can do this

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:05.020
<v Teacher>if it's regular. Maybe it's irregular and we try it and we make a mistake.

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:08.860
<v Teacher>So for example, <b>salir</b> is <i>to leave</i> or <i>to go out</i>.

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:11.820
<v Teacher>If we apply this rule, what are we going to come up with?

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:12.460
<v Student><b>Salo.</b>


00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:13.740
<v Teacher>But it's wrong;

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:16.060
<v Teacher>it's <b>salgo</b>.

00:06:15.260 --> 00:06:24.780
<v Teacher>So it's one of those <b>-go</b> instead of <b>-o</b> like <b>vengo</b>, <i>I'm coming</i>: <b>Tengo.</b> <b>Tengo</b>, <i>I have</i>; <b>salgo</b>, <i>I leave, I'm going out</i>.

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:26.380
<v Teacher>The quite common verbs,

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:31.340
<v Teacher>we tend to find in all languages that the most common verbs are the most irregular.

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:36.300
<v Teacher><b>Esperar</b>, <b>esperar</b>, means <i>to wait</i> and <i>to hope</i>.

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:39.040
<v Teacher>Which is interesting and it's accurate enough.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:42.320
<v Teacher>I mean you're not doing much more than waiting when you hope.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:45.120
<v Teacher>We have it in the word <i>desperate</i> actually.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:49.680
<v Teacher><i>Des-</i> is <i>un-</i>, and you're hopeless when you're desperate.

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.800
<v Teacher>So <b>esperar</b> is <i>to wait</i> or <i>to hope</i>.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:56.040
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I'm waiting</i>, or <i>I'm hoping</i>, or <i>I wait</i>, or <i>I hope</i>?

00:06:56.680 --> 00:06:57.880
<v Student><b>Espero.</b>

00:06:57.880 --> 00:06:58.759
<v Teacher><b>Espero.</b>

00:06:58.759 --> 00:07:01.080
<v Teacher>Now how do you say <i>he waits</i>?

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:02.000
<v Student><b>Espere.</b>

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:11.480
<v Teacher>I'm really glad you made that mistake actually. Because it's a wonderful point to elaborate on.

00:07:11.139 --> 00:07:17.620
<v Teacher>Before we touch a verb, we want to take one split-second to go <b>esperar</b>: <i>-ar</i> verb.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:19.300
<v Teacher>Otherwise what happens?

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:25.940
<v Teacher>Our brain hears /e/-/e/ from <b>esperar</b>, and it wants to put an /e/.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:35.000
<v Teacher>What your mind is doing there, putting an <i>e</i> because you have <b>espe-</b> and it fits better, is actually even ingrained in other languages. For example, in Turkish you have something called vowel harmony.

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:39.100
<v Teacher>And when you're adding on suffixes, there's like

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:47.520
<v Teacher>two or four, depending on the suffix, two or four different versions of that suffix that you can add on so it can agree with the vowel before.

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:50.480
<v Teacher>So there's something in your mind that would prefer an <i>e</i> there.

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:52.080
<v Teacher>Of course because it's <b>espe-</b>

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:57.960
<v Teacher>and like I said you even see this formalized in other languages, like in this phenomenon of vowel harmony.

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:03.240
<v Teacher>So to stop that process from happening, you must run back to the "to" form and then you take control.

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:05.340
<v Student><b>Espera.</b>

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:06.220
<v Teacher><b>Espera.</b>

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:11.259
<v Teacher>And <b>espera</b> means <i>he/she/it/you</i> (formal) <i>wait</i> or <i>are waiting</i>, <i>is waiting</i>.

00:08:11.259 --> 00:08:12.380
<v Teacher>We can build the rest.

00:08:12.380 --> 00:08:14.300
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>they wait</i>?

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:16.139
<v Student><b>Esperan.</b>

00:08:16.139 --> 00:08:19.740
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>they're waiting for me</i>, we don't need the word for <i>for</i>,

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:22.220
<v Teacher>it's just like <i>they await me</i>.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:23.659
<v Teacher>We don't need the word for <i>for</i>.

00:08:23.659 --> 00:08:25.979
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>they await me</i>?

00:08:26.599 --> 00:08:29.240
<v Student><b>Esperanme</b> - sorry, <b>me esperan.</b>

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:30.440
<v Teacher>The only option there because it's a changed verb. <b>Me esperan.</b>

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:32.599
<v Teacher><i>They're not waiting for me</i>:

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:33.560
<v Student><b>No me esperan.</b>

00:08:33.560 --> 00:08:35.640
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No me esperan.</b> <i>I want to know why they're not waiting for me. I want to know</i>:

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:38.820
<v Student><b>Quiero saber.</b>

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:40.979
<v Teacher><i>Why</i>:

00:08:40.979 --> 00:08:43.219
<v Student><b>Por qué no me esperan.</b>

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:49.240
<v Teacher>Very good. <b>Quiero saber por qué no me esperan.</b> Well done.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:53.880
<v Student>I was just very happy that I remembered <b>saver</b> finally.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:56.920
<v Teacher>Ah good. <b>Saber</b> though with a <i>b</i>.

00:08:57.560 --> 00:08:59.400
<v Student><b>Saber</b>, ah.

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:00.120
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:00.360 --> 00:09:01.320
<v Student>Isn't it from <i>savvy</i>?

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:03.279
<v Teacher>Yeah there is a grey area between <i>v</i> and <i>b</i>.

00:09:03.519 --> 00:09:06.160
<v Teacher>So it will change between languages.

00:09:06.160 --> 00:09:07.839
<v Teacher>Actually a very nice example of this is the word for <i>vocabulary</i>.

00:09:07.839 --> 00:09:11.199
<v Teacher><i>Vocabulary</i> in Spanish is <b>vocabulario</b>.

00:09:11.199 --> 00:09:13.759
<v Teacher><b>Vocabulario.</b> It's spelled with a <i>v</i>.

00:09:13.759 --> 00:09:16.399
<v Teacher>But the word for <i>mouth</i> in Spanish is <b>boca</b>, spelled with a <i>b</i>.

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:19.980
<v Teacher>Now of course <b>vocabulario</b> is coming from <b>boca</b>.

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:23.020
<v Teacher>Your vocabulary is your "mouth-ulary".

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:25.900
<v Teacher>This gives us another rule, actually.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:27.500
<v Teacher>Words ending <i>-ary</i> will become <b>-ario</b>.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:30.860
<v Teacher>So <i>necessary</i>:

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:32.660
<v Student><b>Necesario.</b>

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:33.860
<v Teacher><i>Contrary</i>:

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:35.620
<v Student><b>Contrario.</b>

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:37.060
<v Teacher>Good.
